"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-51-year-old-skateboarder-andy-macdonald-time-of-his-life-paris-olympics\", \"text\": \"PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 At first glance, Andy Macdonald looks like his opponents at La Concorde skate park, whipping down into the bowl and flying above it, transitioning from body varial 540 to madonna to nollie kickflip. But then he takes off his helmet to reveal his gray hair.\\u00c2  That nollie kickflip? He invented it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094in 1993. Macdonald, 51, has been skateboarding since before all but one of his opponents inOlympic men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s park skateboardingwere born.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s got a minivan,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Alex Sorgente, a 26-year-old representing Italy. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s got three kids. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s such, like, a soccer dad. But he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s out here competing against us. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s so rad.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Macdonald, who became the oldest Olympic skateboarder since the sport joined the program in Tokyo, finished 18th of 22 in the preliminaries in Wednesday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s park event and did not advance to the final. But standing here in his \\\"Team GB\\\" dad hat, knee-length basketball shorts and sock tan, looking as if he says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cLooks like we got here just in time!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d when a line forms behind him and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTime to rock and roll!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d when he leaves a restaurant, he is thrilled.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cPeople are like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Are you going for the gold?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098If they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re giving away gold medals for whoever has the most fun, I got it wrapped up!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  He adds, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was trying to represent, like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Hey, this is fun, no matter what age you are.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 This is, like, the coolest, funnest, most inclusive thing that you can do. And it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s my livelihood. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m lucky enough that I can make a living doing it. But it keeps me young. Skateboarding is my fountain of youth. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been doing it since I was 12 years old. And I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m 51 and still enjoying every minute of it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Most of his peers have not even gotten to Ponce de Leon in history class yet. Coco Yoshizawa, 14, of Japan, won the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s street skateboarding event last week\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094which made her the oldest Olympic champion in the history of the event, since in Tokyo, her countrywoman Momiji Nishiya, 13, took first place. The men tend to be a bit older\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the medalists in Macdonald\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s event were Keegan Palmer, 21, of Australia; Tom Schaar, 24, of the United States; and Sorgente\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094but a quarter of the field need their parents\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 permission to see an R-rated movie.\\u00c2  Except for one. Dallas Oberholzer, 49, of South Africa, is Olympic skateboarding\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s other grandfather, and although he finished last on Wednesday, he too is having a great time. Macdonald is a legend of the sport who was last in Paris nearly two decades ago to do a demonstration at the Grand Palais with Tony Hawk, the most famous skateboarder ever; Oberholzer, who has no sponsors, rented out his apartment in Cape Town to finance his trips to Olympic qualifiers.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAs an elder,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Oberholzer says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m here to look out over the younger generation, so I can report back, and I can approach these world skate guys and go, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Hey, you know what?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Because these young people are not going to have a voice, and I sure as s*** ain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t scared of being a punk and having a voice.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  As the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094which many skateboarders contend is more of an art\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094becomes dominated by young kids, Oberholzer wants to maintain the culture that has given him so much. He sees it especially in opposition to sports such as soccer, where the Canadian women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s team was recently hit with penalties for illegally filming opponents\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 practices.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe as skateboarders really need to come together\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094as we do,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think we rise above all the other sporting codes when you see how united we are. There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s no spying on each other with drones. Andy Mac was giving me tips the other day because I was doing something wrong. We\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re helping each other, and we just want each other to have the best session possible.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  That perhaps explains why Macdonald\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s fellow skateboarders were so thrilled when he qualified for the Olympics. He is American, but his father, Roderick, was born in Luton, England, which allowed Macdonald to take a shot at making the Great Britain team. He won 23 X Games gold medals in vertical, or vert, skateboarding, but since that is not an Olympic discipline, he competed in park. Because vert tends to take place on a wooden halfpipe and a fall gives you a chance to slide down a bit before you crash, it is much easier on the body than park, where everything is cement and you hit bottom immediately. Macdonald laughs when he sees teenagers wipe out and pop back up and try again, knowing a similar injury would have him out for a week.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhen he made it, we were like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098F***, you deserve it,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Danny Leon, 29, of Spain, with a laugh. (He is perhaps Macdonald\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s biggest fan, because when Macdonald is not around, Leon is the grandfather. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOne girl asked me, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Are you married?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098No, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098But you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re 29!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d)  And they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re all having fun. Macdonald is willing to take the jabs for his wardrobe (\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cColors [from the] 80s,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Leon. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEverything now is black and white\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d) and his equipment (\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe skull on his board graphic,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Luigi Cini, 22, of Brazil. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSkulls are kind of, like, old-man stuff.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d), but there is one point he wishes to clarify: It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not a minivan. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI drive a Volkswagen camper van,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI drove it for 20-plus years. It was the beachgoer, taking the family camping and stuff. And I just finally sold it and got an electric car. So I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m getting with the times.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Stephanie Apstein is a senior writer covering baseball and Olympic sports for Sports Illustrated, where she started as an intern in 2011 and has since covered a dozen World Series and three Olympics. She has twice won top honors from the Associated Press Sports Editors, and her work has been included in the Best American Sports Writing book series. She graduated from Trinity College with a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in French and Italian, and has a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Columbia University.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. 